{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_fiji_ver02/data/sn83030214/00175039338/1908041901/0347.xml":{"full_text":"NEW-YORK DAILY TRIBUNE. SUNDAY, APRIL 19, 1908.\nwhy\na\nTHE TRIBUNE'S FOREIGN NEWS.\nIDOL IN MANCHESTER\nALL EYES ON CHURCHILL.\nHis Defeat Not Likely Unless the\nLiquor Trade Enters Contest.\nIDOL IN MANCHESTER\nALL EYES ON CHURCHILL.\nHis Defeat Not Likely Unless the\nLiquor Trade Enters Contest.\n|Special by French Cable to The Tribune.\n[Copyright, 1808, iy Tne Tribune Association.\nGeodon. BR 18.\u2014Winston Churchill has\ntaken the centre of the stage at Manchester as\nthe chief trustee for free trade. His defeat will\nbe a sign that a stronghold of Cobdenism has\nbeen converted to tariff reform. This is not\nlikely to happen unless the liquor trade takes\npossession of the district for the sake of smash\ntng the licensing bill. Mr. Churchill has con\ncentrated public attention upon the defence of\nfree trade and has employed an argument easily\nunderstood at Manchester\u2014namely, that India\nwill adopt protection if England reverts to it,\nand that Lancashire 1 iose her best market.\nThat ought to settle question, when Man-\u2019\nchester goods go mainly to India. And there\nis another consideration counting heavily in Mr.\nChurchill's favor\u2014namely, the advantage which\nthe trades unionists will derive from placing the\npresident of the Board of Trade under obliga\ntions to them when he is the future arbiter\nbetween capital and organized labor. Yet the\nopposition is making a tremendous effort to\nwreck him, and when there are sO many Cross\ncurrents they may succeed. Mr. Churchill is\nconducting his canvass with frankness and\nastuteness, speaking as effectively as Lord\nRandolph Churchill used to do and displaying\nsobriety of judgment. He is the idol of Man\nchester, is called everywhere by his first name\nand is listened to as though he were another\nCobden. The new Chancellor of the Exchequer\ngoes to Lancashire to help him, and all the re\nsources of the Liberal administration are behind\nhim. If the Liberals cannot hold the seat under\nthese circumstances, the reaction against them\nhas become irresistible.\nthe\nPrime Minister Asquith is in the highest spirits\nafter the success of his first attempt at Cab\ninet carpentry. He gives every one who talks\nwith him the impression that a strong Prime\nMinister has entered the stage and that heads\nof departments will carry out his leading pol\nicies instead of being preoccupied with their\nown work and legislative measures of their\nown invention. I. NX. F\nCHURCHILL'S HARD FIGHT\nPresident of Board of Trade Cam\npaigning\u2014His Mother Helps.\nLondon, April 18.\u2014The recent reconstruction of\nthe Cabinet which came about as a result of the re\ntirement of Sir Henry Campbell-Bannerman and the\nassumption of the office of Premier by Herbert H.\nAsquith has plunged ihe country into a miniature\nelection. Not less than seven by-elections have\nbeen made necessary to fill the vacancies created by\nthe Cabinet changes. Four of these will be decided\nduring the coming week. By far the most interest\ning will be held to return a member from the North\nwest Division of Manchester, where the fate of\nWinston Churchill, who is seeking re-election on his\nelevation to the presidency of the Board of Trade,\nwill be a surer index of the country\u2019s estimate of\nthe past two years of Radical rule than are the ver\ndicts of the smaller constituencies which recently\nhave gone against the government This contest\nwill be hard fought, and the political fighters in both\nthe leading parties are preparing for the fray. Mr.\nChurchill wiil again be opposed by W. Jovnson\nHicks, who contested this seat in the Unionist in\nteresis at the last general election in Manchester.\nThere 1s also a Socialist candidate in the field, but\nhe does not count much.\nThe Associated Press\nMr. Churchill is showing his customary energy in\nas fiercely waged a contest as has been seen in this\ncountry in Years. After a brief Good Friday truce\nhe has addressed not less than half a dozen meet\nings to-day, four of which were in the open air in\ndifferent parts.of the constituency. Mr. Churchill's\nmother, Mrs. Cornwallis West, better known as\nLady Randolph Churchill, is repeating her tactics\nof the last election. She accompanies her son to\nthe platforms, anc is untiring in her work among\nthe doubtful groups of \u00ableciors. Among these must\nbe reckoned the Hebrews, the Roman Catholics and\nwe Irish Nationalists. All three groups are de\nwinding pledges regarding the alien exclusion bill,\nducation and home rule respectively. All three\nsoted for Mr. Churchill at the last election, and the\ndefection of any one of these groups mighi easily\nspell defeat on April 24, the date of the election.\nThe woman suffragists are proving a thorn in the\nside of the voung statesman. Although Mr. Church\nill has declared himself in favor of woman suffrage,\nthe women are overrunning the constituency in fa\nvor of the Unionist candidate, declaring that the\nrecent attitude of the members of the Cabinet and\nef Parliament proves that the government has no\nintention of forcing the cause of women to the front.\nThe great importance attached to this fight is\nmeen in the fact that the Chancellor of the Exchequer\n&#nd other ministers, disregarding precedent in this\ncountry, will address not less than ten meetings in\nManchester on the ove of the election, In the hardly\nanticipated eventuality of an adverse result some\ncomplacent Radical holding a \u201csafe\u201d seat will re\nceive political inducement to resign in favor of Mr.\nChurchill. onsequently, beyond the loss of pres\ntige to both himself and the government he repre\nsents, Mr. Churchill's position in the Cabinet will\nnot be gffected.\nThe Drink\nQuestion\nThe Drink\nThe Drink\nQuestion\n11S\u20ac of alcoholic stimu\n2\nnn means conhned 10 The \u20acXCesSSIVE\nThe amount of coffee containing a poisonous alkaloid\nto be over\ncaffeme\u2014which 1s consumed in this country,\neli million hagas a vear.\n\u201cnervous prostration\u201d in America than\nAnd theres more\nanvwhe re orl the globe.\nvou really want strong nerves and a clear brain, stop\ncoffee and use the wholesome cereal beverage,\nPOSTUM\nIt is made from wheat, including the vital phosphates from\nthe grains, placed there by nature for rebuilding brain and\nnerve cells.\n\u201cThere\u2019s a Reason\u2019 or\nPOSTUM\n1s bv no means confined to the excessive use of alcoholic stimu\nlants.\nThe amount of coffee containing a poisonous alkaloid\ncaffeine\u2014which is consumed in this country, is said to be over\nten million bags a year.\nAnd there's more \u201cnervous prostration\u201d in America than\nanvwhere on the globe.\nI+ vou really want strong nerves and a clear brain, stop\ncoffee and use the wholesome cereal beverage,\nSIR EDWARDGREY FIRM\nDiplomats Seek to Entangle Him in\nMacedonian Compromise.\nEA Rl Rep AR hg TT oe\nLondon, April 18.\u2014While a million holiday\nseekers have been sent out of London for Easter\nwith the warning from Colonel Yorke that the\nengine drivers are so heavily overworked that\nthey are likely to fall asleep at their posts and\noverrun the danger signal, as at Shrewsbury,\nthere is no ground for uneasiness that the risks\nof a war of injustice are increased through\nthe strenuous labors of statesmen like Sir Ed\nward Grey, who \u2018are responsible for the peace\nof the world. It is not likely that he will aban\ndon the high ground taken on the Macedonian\nquestion, although Russian and German diplo\nmatists are seeking to entangle him in compro\nmises, nor that he will relax his vigilance on the\nCongo question, on which he is working hand in\nhand with Secretary Root to secure the fulfil\nment of the treaty guarantees for justice and\nhumanity to the natives.\nNor is there serious reason for any apprehen\nsion that the labors of the British Ambassador\nin Washington and the American Ambassador\nhere for the settlement of outstanding ques\ntions between America and England will fafl\nthrough the exigencies of party politics or safe\nguards for the protection of the Senate's consti\ntutional rights. I. FF\nEASTER HOUSE PARTIES.\nQueen's Maid of Honor a Bride\u2014\nLiberal Receptions.\nIMOPYLIEML, JED, 13Y SAFE AA AM he\nLondon, April 18.\u2014Easter parties at the coun\ntry houses are mainly small affairs, as shooting\ncannot be provided for the entertainment of\nguests and the hunting season has closed.\n\nThe Duchess of Westminster, the Duchess of\nSomerset, Lady Beauchamp, Lady Londonderry\nand Lady Plymouth are among the hostesses,\nand Lady Arlington has theatricals at Crichel.\nA series of Easter weddings opens with the\nappearance of one of Lady Ruby Elliott's\nbridesmaids as a bride. This is the Queen's\nmaid of honor, Miss Margaret Dawnay, who will\nbe married to the Rev. Roland Grant at Chapel\nRoyal, St. James's.\nThe Liberal hostesses may bestir themselves\nwhen Parliament reassembles, but there will be\nno gayety until the return of the King from\nChristiania. The air is heavy with polities, and\nthe dinner parties and Liberal receptions are\nconsidered dull by the smart people, who have\ngone to the Continent for livelier entertainment\nfor the next three weeks. IN. FF.\nLUM Igiit, AWWO, Uy 140 1TI0UNe ASSOCIalioll.\nLondon, April 18.\u2014There was a holiday crowd\nat the Haymarket to-night for the first per\nformance of Sydney Grundy's farce, \u201cA Fearful\nJoy.\u201d The original, a French play, was writ\nten forty wears ago for the purpose \u00bbf ridicul\ning the ordinary stage Lothario. The adapter\nhias borroved (he main ideas and dressed and\nrefitted them to suit himself. What the play\nwrights cynically call \u2018\u2018the eternal triangle\u201d\nwas never treated less seriously, and since\nthere was much laughter during the evening\nit was presumably a broadly humorous farce.\nMrs. Langtry was the theatrical, sentimental\nwife with a variety of handsome gowns, and\nArthur Bourchier the easygoing, stupid hus\nband. The comedy was supplied mainly by Al\nlan Aynesworth as a profligate who was con\nstantly paying the piper and never getting in\ntune. 3-4 by Edmund Maurice as an audacious\nvalet who Kept everybody under surveillance\nand had all the material for a divorce suit in\nhis own possession.\nThere will be many revivals and changes\nin programme at the theatres in the next\nthree weeks. The managers are making stren\nuons efforts to find out what the public wants,\nand a majority of them are probably drawing\nblanks in the lottery. There will be fresh ex\nperiments with American plays, \u201c'Way Down\nEast\u201d heing among the earliest at Aldwych,\nwithh the company already on the ground re\nhearsing and the general manager threatening\nlegal proceedings against a condensed version\nunder another title. John Hare \u201cwill reappear\nas the Gay lord Quex at the Garrick, and\nMrs. Ward's \u201cThe Marriage of William Ashe\u201d\nwill be staged at Terry's.\nMeanwhile Shakespeare holds the field at\nHis Majesty's and the Stratford, and Pinero's\nnew play is coming on at St. James's, with a\ncomedy by Henry Arthur Jones reserved by\nCharles Frohman for autumn. I NF\na rs\nQuestion\n[Special by French Cable to The Tribune.]\nrConvright 1808. by The Tribune Association.]\n[Special by French Cable to The Tribune]\nGRUNDY'S NEW FARCE,\n\u201cAd Fearful Joy\u201d Produced at the\nHaymarket.\nSpecial by French Cable to The Tribune.)\nPLAGUE AT 1A ClIAVRA DENIED\nEr A wii 5. 3 het fi 8 ll Rl FF FRAN hd dL Sl\nWillemstad, April 17.\u2014 Passengers who are await\ning here the arrival of the next Italian steamer\nfrom Venezuelan ports are much concerned on ac\ncount of the quarantine measures taken at Port\nI.imon and Colon against vessels from Venezuela\nbecause of the alleged existence of bubonic plague\nat l.a Guayra. The Venezuelan authorities refuse\nto admit tht the plague exists at that port.\nNEW-YORK DAILY TRIBUNE. SUNDAY, APRIL 19, 1908.\na A\nBLOW AT IMPERIALISM\nPASSIVE ROLE FOR U. S.\nFrench Opinion of Refusal of Bat\ntleships Appropriation.\n[Special by French Cable to The Tribune.\nA UI Rp AI gl rT TTT th pe TT\nParis, April 18.\u2014The refusal of Congress to\ngrant the appropriation for four battleships asked\nby President Roosevelt is widely discussed in the\nFrench press, the trend of opinion being that it\nis an indication that the United States is willing\nto confine herself henceforth to a passive role\nin foreign affairs and that imperialism is losing\nground all along the line.\n\u201cLe Temps\u201d says: \u201cFor the last ten years\nthe American policy has changed its character,\nand it is now too late to return to the simple\nlife of earlier vears. But the Americans do not\naccept the logical consequences of the change.\nThey see th\u00e9 object, but do not desire to adopt\nthe necessary means. President Roosevelt's\nnaval policy consists in creating these means.\nTherefore Congress, sooner or later, will take\nit up again. When one is right one always\nends by carrying the day, and success is only\na question of time.\u201d\nOn the same subject \u201cThe Radical\u2019 says:\n\u201cPresident Roosevelt is a great partisan of the\nincrease of the naval force of the United States.\nHe desires a powerful American fleet, not, as\nhe savs, to be used as an instrument of aggres\nsion and conquest, but in order to be ready\nwhen the moment comes for its employment.\nNo nation can be respected that isnot strong.\u201d\nThe action of the American Congress has\nelicited from Paul Benazet, an authority on\nnaval matters, a statement that attracts con\nsiderable attention. M. Benazet, after making\ncertain criticisms on the state of the French\nnavy, says that in 1915 France will possess\ntwelve battleships, while at the same time,\nthanks to the continuity of its efforts toward\nthe uninterrupted execution of a plan estab\nlished with judgment, Germany will possess\nmore than thirty battleships, equal to the most\npowerful English ones. It is absurd. M. Benazet\ncontinues, to suppose that the Kaiser is having\nsuch a large number of battleships built for the\nsimple pleasure of protecting his international\ncommerce. If he is forging such formidable\narms with so much care it is because he counts\non using them, either in war against England\nor France or against both at the same time.\n\u00abFT 50\nTHE \"DUKE OF GANDIA\u201d\nParisians Don\u2019t Think It Adds to\nSwinburne\u2019s Reputation.\n[Special by French Cable to The Tribune.]\nIT Copyright, 1908. by The Tribune Association.\nParis, April 18. \u2014Several members of the\nFrench Academy who are familiar with English\nliterature have received copies of Algernon\nSwinburne\u2019's latest work, \u201cThe Duke of Gandia.\u201d\nThe feeling expressed by French men of letters\nIs one of extreme courtesy to a poet of Swin\nburne\u2019's achievements and at the same time of\nregret that in spite of certain transient out\nbursts of forcible dialogue the versification is\nlamentably jerky, lacking the harmonious flow\nthat one has a right to expect from the author\nof Scottish trilogy and \u201cTristram of Lyonesse.\u201d\nSwinburne is compared to Richepin, and the\nEnglish poet's \u201cDuke of Gandia\u201d is regarded as\nnot adding in any way to his reputation.\nPlon Nourrit publishes \u201cJoseph de Maistre et\nBlacas.\u201d The book gives their hitherto unknown\nletters and correspondence, and for the first\ntime sets forth the story of their strong friend\nship. The pericd from 1804 to 1820 discloses\nthe extraordinary activity of de Maistre, who\nwas the ablest opponent of the French Revolu\ntion, and reveals the intrigues of the Russian\ncourt with Blacas, the representative of the\nHouse of Bourbon. The work is preceded by an\nintroduction, notes and commentaries by Ernest\nDaudet. Irom Nilsson comes \u201cLes Promenades\nd'un Artiste au Mus\u00e9e du Louvre,\u201d by Jean\nFrancois Raffaelli, with a preface by Maurice\nBarres. It is an informal walk through the\nLouvre Gallery with the essentially modern\nParisian painter, who in a simple, unpretentious\nway explains the technique of the old masters\nand the secrets of their studios. Raffaelli has\ndevoted years to the subject, and his little book,\nclever and sprightly, is a valuable acquisition\nfor art students.\nThe publishing house of Emile Paul issues an\nadditional work in the series of \u201cLes Reines\nde I'Emigration.\u201d This time the great lady is\nAnne de la Force, Comtesse de Balbi, described\nby Vicomte de Reiset.\nFrom Mercure de France comes \u201cLes Scru\npuleg de Sganarelle,\u201d a novel by Henri de Ree\ngnier, the action of which passes in the time of\nMoli\u00e9re and is based upon a feminine intrigue,\nat once amusing and tragic.\nProfessor Baker's lectures at the Sorbonne\n\u201cand the French universities continue to be de\ncidedly successful. The Harvard professor has\nreturned to Paris from Rheims and Nancy,\nwhere he delivered lectures at the universities,\nand on April 20 he starts on a southern tour\nto lecture on Shakespeare at the universities of\nDijon, Lyons, Grenoble, Marseilles, Montpellier,\nToulouse, Bordeaux, Rennes and Caen, finishing\nup at Lille on May 20. His theme, \u201cThe Future\nof the Poetic Drama in the United States,\u201d is\nkeeniy appreciated by French university men,\nwho feel convinced that our country will have\ngooner or later a poetic drama essentially\n\n\nAmer\nican. $F 33\nKrasnoyarsk, Siberia, Apri] 17 A lieutenant of\nthe army named Masloff and a sergeant were shot\nto death here to-day, after having been found\nguilty by a court martial on the charge that they\nhad led the attfick which took place last June on\nthe guardhouse and detention prison of Krasno\nYarsk.\n\nTO CPEN SOUTH AMERICAN RAIl WAV\n\nRio de Janeiro, April 18.\u2014M. Calmon, the Minister\nof Railways, will leave here to-morrow to open the\nfirst section of 360 miles of the new railroad be\ntween here and the city of Goyaz. When the entire\nline is completed it will be possible to make the\nJourney from Rio de Janeiro to Goyaz in two days,\nat the present time the trip requires three weeks\n\n\nPRESIDENT SENDS \u201cPHOTO\u201d TO POET\nMarseilles, April 15.\u2014The American Consul Gen\neral here, Robert Skinner, has presented to the ven\nerable Provencal poet, Frederic Mistral, a photo\ngraph of President Roosevelt bearing his autograph.\nThis pittyre was sent especially (o th\u00e9 poet by Mr.\nLlouseyv elt.\nPARIS LOCKOUT VIRTUALLY ENDED.\nee em fb\nParis, April 17.-The lockout affecting a great\nnumber of masons, bricklayers and allied work\nmen which began on April 4 virtually ended to\nday. The men generally deserted the leaders of\nthe mevement und signed terms with the con\ntractors, who have announced that work will be\nresumed on April 21.\nBRING BODY OF MAN SYRIAN SHOT\nNaples, April 18. ~The body of Bernard Warken\ntin, of Newton, Kan., left here to-day on board the\ntteamer Koenig Albert for New York Mr. Ware\nkentin was accidentally shot and kiled by a Syrian\nin g railroad train near Damascus a little over two\nweeks ago. The body is accompanied by the\nwidow and son of the dead man.\nTWO OFFICERS EXECUTE\nAID TO CLEMENCEAU\n\nMoorish Attack Arouses Public Sup\nport of His African Policy.\nI1Snacial hv French (able to The Tribune.\n[Special by French Cable to The Tribune.\nConvright 1808 bv The Tribune Association.\nParis, April 18.\u2014The news of the Moorish\nattack upon the column of Colonel Pierron and\nthe result of the recent fighting has the\neffect of arousing public opinion to the neces\nsity of taking still more energetic measures\nagainst the Moors. Frenchmen at last thor\noughly realize that to shirk from establish\ning order in Morocco would now endanger the\nwhole colony of Algeria and irretrievably de\nstroy French influence in North Africa. Spirited\ndescriptions of the gallant conduct of the officers\napd men are read in Paris and in the depart\nments with eagerness, eliciting everywhere gen\nuine enthusiasm. The military critics declare\nthat the efficiency and fighting qualities of the\nFrench soldier have been put.tosthe most thor\nough test that they have experienced since 187\nand implicit confidence is expressed on a\nsides in the sterling qualities of the democ\nratized Republican army, so severely found fault\nwith by the military men of the old r\u00e9gimes.\nThe battle of Menabba has thus had a whole\nsome influence on the French nation, and the\nClemenceau Cabinet is now more warmly sup\nported in its North African policy than ever\nbefore. Cc. B.\nLUNCHEON FOR PAINTER.\nPilgrims Honor Edwin A. Abbey\u2014\nImportant Art Sales Coming.\n[Special by French Cable to The Tribune.\nF Yaar vt or Bs YEE Iuer Tina Tet estes: A aateenretot drm\nEPS AY YW 40S LHLHO00NMNIEF  4RHENR=.ALIN. 2\nLondon, April 18.\u2014The Pilgrims are interpret\ning the completion of Edwin A. Abbey's paint\nings for the dome of the Harrisburg Capitol as\nan international event by giving a luncheon for\nhim at the Savoy. James J. Shannon and John\nS. Sargent are expected to divide the honors at\nthe next Academy.\nArt sales at Christie's are suspended for a\nshort interval, but are likely to be unusually im\nportant in May and June. Among the collec\ntions to be dispersed will be those of Stephen\nGeorge Holland and Humphrey Roberts, the\nlatter containing some of the best Millais pict\nures and brilliant works by Corot and other\nFrench masters. LX. RB\nBRAZIL AND PARAGUAY AT PEACE.\nIntervention of Argentina Brings About\nBetter Relations.\n\nRio de Janeiro, April 18.\u2014There is reason to be\nlieve that the relations between Brazil and Para\nguay, which for a long time past have been\nstrained, are about to enter upon a period of dis\ntinct improvement. This is an outcome of the\nvisit to Rio de Janeiro of Sefior Baez, the Para\nguayan Minister of Foreign Affairs, who brings\nwith him an autograph letter from Dr. Ferreyra,\nPresident of Paraguay, giving assurances of the\nsympathy and friendship of his government with\nBrazil.\nIt is understood that Argentina was instru\nmental in bringing this visit about. A semioffi\ncial communication from Asuncion, the capital of\nParaguay, sets forth that this visit marks the be\nginning of an entirely new departure in South\nAmerican politics.\nRUSSIAN AMBASSADOR TO JAPAN.\nEmperor Approves Senator MalevskyMala\nvitch\u2014Baron Motono for St. Petersburg.\nSt. Petersburg, April 18.\u2014Emperor Nicholas has\napproved the appointment of Senator Malevsky\nMalavitch to be Russian Ambassador to Japan.\nThe diplomatic post at Tokio has just been raised\nfrom a legation to an embassy. The Foreign Office\nhas communicated with Tokio, and learns that M.\nMalevsky-Malavitch is persona grata.\nJapan has not yet taken formal steps in the\nmatter of nominating an ambassador to Russia,\nbut it is understood that Baron Motono, the pres\nent minister here, will be promoted as a reward for\nhis successful handling of the recent RussoJap\nanese negotiations,\nPRIVATE KILLS COLOR SERGEANT.\nIntoxicated Man Resents Reproof with Bul\nlet in Ontario Barracks.\nLondon, Ont., April 18.\u2014Color Sergeant Harrv L.\nLloyd of the 28th Regiment, of Stratford. was shot\nand killed by Private Moyer, of the Royal Canadian\nRegiment, at Wolsey Barracks at midnight last\nnight.\nMoyer appeared in an intoxicated condition, and\nLloyd reprimanded him and ordered him to his\nquarters. Shortly afterward an orderly reported an\nunusual noise coming from Moyer's room. and in\nformed Lioyd, who, with the orderly, went to in\nvestigate. As they opened the door Moyer covered\nLloyd with a rifle, shouted \u201cHands up!\u201d and in the\nnext instant shot him through the breast. Drop\nping the rifle he selzed a revolver and chased the\norderly. who escaped injury. Mover escaped in the\ndarkness and has not vet been captured. Lloyd\nlived onlv a few minutes.\nPOPE TO ARCHBISHOP O'CONNELL\nRome, April 18.\u2014The Pope has written an auto\ngraph letter to Archbishop O'Connell in connection\nwith the approaching centennial celebration of the\nerection of the See of Boston. He congratulates the\nArchbishop warmly upon the progress of (atholi\ncism in his see and praises the lovalty of the clergy\nand the faithful zea! of the Archbishop. He also\nthanks the Archbishop for a contribution of Peter's\npene amounting to $40,000.\n\nGENERAL LINEVITCH SERIOUSLY ILL\nSt. Petersburg, April 18.\u2014Lieutenant General\nLinevitch, aide-de-camp to Emperor Nicholas, and\ntormerly commander in chief of the Russian army\nin. Manchuria, is ill with pneumonia. Serious ap\nprehension is entertained as to his recovery, owing\n10 the general's advanced age.\nWRECKAGE OF SAILING SHIP FOUND\nVictoria, B. C., April 18. \u2014Indications that some\nunidentified vessel, seemingly a large sailing ship,\nhas met disaster, probably with loss of life, off\nthe Vancouver Island coast, were given in a dispatch\nreceived last night from W. H. Baykin, lighthouse\nkeeper of Carmanah Point, telling of a large quan\ntity of wreckage which came ashore Thursday night\nsix miles east of Carmanali.\nU. S. CUSTOMS OFFICIAL DROWNED.\nFort Frances, Ont, April 18 \u2014-Willilam Braok,\nAmerican customs officer here, was drowned yes\nterday while endeavoring to run the rapids in a\ncanoe. Brack came from St. Paul, where his par\nents live.\nThe Loly carpet of Turkey is a gorgeous plece of\nred velvet embroldered with gold. It takes a vear\nto make the carpet, and the Bultan of Turkey then\nintrusts it to the Egyptian pllgrims to place on the\ntomb of the Prophet atl Mecca. At the end of that\ntime it is replaced by another carpet, and is re\nturned to Cairo with great ceremany. The right to\ncarry the carpet has been handed down from camel\nto \u00a2amel in the male line for hundreds of years,\nA religious festival which plays an important part\nin Indian life is the Nagpanchami, which occurs in\nJuly and August. The monsoon, or rainy season, is\nsupposed to end with this feast, and it is there\nfore more extensively celebrated in the coast dis\ntricts than in the inland parts. It is the great holi\nday for seafaring men and fisherfolk generally.\nThe cobra is worshipped, and offerings of milk are\nplaced In shallow dighes in =potz which these rep.\ntiles are known to haunt. Thousands of cocoanuts\nare thrown into the sea.\nCHURCH PEACE PROMISE\nGROWTH OF TOLERATION.\nBoth Parties Can Welcome Uni\nversities Bill.\nBB a Je oe\n{Special by French Cable to The Tribune.\n{CopyTight, 1008, Dy 1he ITridune ASSOCI1LIOn.\nLondon, April 18.\u2014The approach of Easter is\nheralded by the promise of peace between the\nfree and established churches respecting edu\ncation. The Welsh disestablishment, which Sir\nHenry Campbell-Bannerman talked about .for\nnext year, has ceased to be a live issue, and the\nWesleyans, instead of hoping for it, are dis\nquieted by the evidence of the largest decline\nin their membership witnessed during half a\ncentury and are not reassured by the fact that\nfinancial support is more generous than ever.\nWhat is a most promising sign in the re\nligious world is the growth of toleration, which\njenables both parties in Parliament to welcome\nMr. Birrell's university bill as an act of justice\nto Roman Catholic Ireland and inspires broad\nminded men with the hope that a round table\nconference can be brought about by which the\neducation wrangle can be stopped on the lines\nproposed by the Bishop of St. Asaph's.\nThere is, apart from the proposed concordat\nbetween the established and free churches, the\npromise of a reawakening of religious activity\nin the preparations for the Pan-Anglican Con\ngress. These are on a larger scale than the or\nganizers of previous reunions have attempted.\nSeven of the biggest halls in the metropolis have\nbeen hired for as many sections of the congress,\nand it will be a conference of worldwide influ\nence, with Anglican Christianity represented\nmore comprehensively than ever before.\nThe Archbishop of Canterbury and Bishop\nDoane are expected to be the master minds of\nthis unique gathering, at which the discussion\nwill not be narrowed to small points of dogma\nor ritual, but broadened to the general obliga\ntions of the Anglican communion to human so\n\nciety, Christian truth and practical mission\nwork in Wesley's great diocese, namely the\nworld. 1 NF\n\n\nHANDS OFF. SAYS RUSSIA.\n\nWants No Interference in Persia\nFErcept from Eneland.\ni\n\nSt. Petersburg, April 18.\u2014The Foreign Office is\nkeenly interested in Russia's little frontier war\nin Persia. It is the first occasion to arise for the\nactive application of Russia's right, under the\nAnglo-Russian agreement, to interfere to preserve\norder in Northern Persia. The operations them\nselves are considered of minor importance, and\nthey will quickly come to an end so soon as the\nsubsidence of the floods permits the removal of\nthe Russian detachments. Russia counts upon the\nhearty suppport of Great Britain and no inter\nference on the part of any other power.\nThe Foreign Office has no further news of fight\ning. The Russian commander telegraphs that the\nPersian inhabitants along the frontier have aban\ndoned their villages and fled to the mountains.\nThe Russian detachment {s still in Persian terri\ntory.\n18.\u2014The situation on the Persian\nfrontier arising from the activity of bands of\nmarauding Kurds has not materially improved.\nThe Persian bandits, who retired into their moun\ntain fastnesses after their first successes against\nthe Russians, again concentrated in force yester\nday and renewed their attack against Belesuvar.\nThe Russians countered with energy. and their\nartillery bombarded several villages in which the\nbrigands had taken shelter.\nThe Russian commmander has received orders\nto disperse and entirely wipe out the brigand\nbands. Reinforcements are being sent in to him\nfrom Baku and Lenkoran. The expedition that\nTiflis, April\nwent from Baku found its flanks menaced by the\nbrigands, and it therefore occupied points in Per\nsian territory in order adequately to protect the\nline of communication. In addition to the losses\npreviously reported the Russians have had seven\nsoldiers killed.\nThe Russian commander says in a report that\nthe Persian authorities have lost their heads en\ntirely and that anarchy reigns in the district. Ad\nvices received here from Tabriz are that the Gov\nernor of that city has received imperative orders\nfrom Teheran to hasten the dispatch of a Persian\n\nforce into the disturbed territory, sending all the\neral of Tiflis,\nto supervise the precautionary mesures Russia is\n\nregular troops available.\nLieutenant General Mistchenko, Governor Gen\nhas left here for the Kars district\ntaking along the Turkish frontier in view of the\nmobilization of Turkish troops on the other side\nof the line. The people of Tiflis are considerably\nconcerned over this situation, but higher military\nofficials now profess confidence that the Turkish\n\nmeasures are not directed against Russia.\nSt. Petersburg, April 18.\u2014The Foreign Office is\nkeenly interested in Russia's little frontier war\nin Persia. It is the first occasion to arise for the\nactive application of Russia's right, under the\nAnglo-Russian agreement, to interfere to preserve\norder in Northern Persia. The operations them\nselves are considered of minor importance, and\nthey will quickly come to an end so soon as the\nsubsidence of the floods permits the removal of\nthe Russian detachments. Russia counts upon the\nhearty suppport of Great Britain and no inter\nference on the part of any other power.\nThe Foreign Office has no further news of fight\ning. The Russian commander telegraphs that the\nPersian inhabitants along the frontier have aban\ndoned their villages and fled to the mountains.\nThe Russian detachment {s still in Persian terri\ntory.\nRUSSIA AND BALKANS.\nM. d'Iswolsky Outlines Attitude\nHope of Agreement.\nSt. Petersburg. April 17.\u2014M. d'Iswoisky, the For\neign Minister, delivered his statement regarding\nthe Balkan situation to the Douma to-day. He\nsaid he was not able to announce any definite step\ntoward the settiement of the Macedonian problem,\nbut that the loyal support of the Russian pro\ngramme by Austria-Hungary, Germany, Italy and\nFrance and its partial approval by reat Britain\nwere full of promise. Reforms in Macedonia were\nimperatively necessary, he said. Unfortunately,\nthere had been no substantial benefits from the\nprevious efforts of the powers in this direction.\nThis failure was due largely to the quarrels and\njealousies among the nationalities which it was\ndesired to benefit. Any new programme would be\nimpossible, unless it shouid be supported by the\nunanimous co-operation of all the powers, and\nRussia was obliged for this reason to reject the\nproposal advanced by Great Britain. The Russian\nplan, the Foreign Minister continued, contained\nneither selfish designs nor dangerous innovations,\nand could be put into execution without danger\nof bringing on a great conflict.\n\n\n\n\nM. d'Iswolsky added that the cardinal principle\nof Russia's present policy was a sound egoism.\nShe needed peace to recuperate from the effects of\nthe struggle with Japan, and she therefore in\ntended, at all cost, to avoid a dissolution of the\nEuropean concert.\nM. d'Iswolsky refused to answer a request for\ninformation regarding the Persian situation.\nThe Douma then adopted the Foreign Office\nbudget and adjourned for the holidays. It will\nreconvene on May o.\nThe Benate to-day confirmed the course of the\nDouma committee, which recommended that M.\nRolubiakin be excluded from the Douma.\nTO CHECK TRUSTS IN RUSSIA.\nDouma Members Plan a Campaign to Curb\nCorporations.\nSt. Petersburg, April i. \u2014A group of Uctobrists\nand other members of the Douma intend to start a\ncampalgn in the House against Yue growth of\ngreat corporations in Russia. It is thelr plan to\ninterpellate the government regarding the {ron and\nsteel trust, now in course of formation, which will\ncontrol 60 per cent of the steel production of Rus\nsia as well as coal and iron mines, and they allege\nthat this trust will drive outsiders into bankruptey.\nThey will ask the government what measures are\nbeing taken to protect the independents and to pre\nvent higher prices.\n\n\nRussia already has legislation against combina\ntions in restraint of trade, but syndicates subject\nto government regulation ars permitted.\nThe Minister of Communication is about to send\na commission of engineers to the United States to\nstudy the construction and operation of steel cars\nin that country.\nIn this week's market little of interest iy des\nveloped. Quotations have moved in no signif\ncant way. Of outside interest scant showing ig\nanywhere. Here and there are advances\u2014few\ndeclines, none of consequence, are recorded\nbut what may be regarded as actual description\nof the market is that duiness has prevailed\nWe have the start of gold exports\u2014merely the\nloaning of money abroad. Crop reports are lesg\nimportant than day by day bulletins represent\u2014\nnot one bad thing showing. The commercial\nagencies make reports that are very favorable\nindicating that collections are readier, and that\nthere is dispesition: on the part of retailers ang\ntheir superiors to increase orders. From Wash.\nington the news is hardly cheerful; there prom.\njses to be no financial relief legislation.\nises to be no financial reier egisation.\nAt the risk of accusations of tiresomeness it\nagain becomes pertinent to point out the funda\nmental, the basic, influences which imperativeiy\ngovern the security market. Back of financial\npanic, indifferent or impervious to local financial\nupheavals, looms the tremendous fact of cone\ntinulng American production of natural and in\ndustrial products. Crops grow and are in eager\ndemand at remunerative prices\u2014to this there is\nno exception. Mills and factories produce come\nmodities for wijich customers stand ready with\norders in hand. Getting away from the pesai\nmistic atmosphere of Wall Street, nothing can\nbe found to warrant apprehension of the future\nWhile it is true that much business etagnation\u2014\nmuch dolefulness\u2014is encountered in the trans\naction of business on Manhattan Island, it is\nequally true that when the observer looks be\nvond these narrow confines sturdy optimism and\nsteady recuperation are visible.\nAs to the agricultural situation, there 13 Hetle\nto be desired. Winter-sown crops are virtually\nassured in abundance\u2014spring-sown crops ter\ntheir seasonal period under auspices virtually\njdeal. And, of transcendental importance, the\ndemand for every product of our soil is urgent.\nIt is already apparent that the year 1508 will\ncontinue the prosperity of the American farmer\nand planter to happy consummation.\nAs to the industrial situation, there is cheering\nevidence that there is to be no trade wears, no\nsenseless slashing of prices, no ruinous compe\ntition. And this is because demand for all man\nufactured products is genuinely great. Since the\nfinancial panic set in there has here and theres\nbeen many an attempt upon the part of com\nsumers to curtail deliveries\u2014to produce an arti\nficial lessening of consumption; but the ever\ngrowing, natural and inevitable demand for\nthose products of the loom, the mill, the foundry\nand the factory, has made it impossible 12\nthwart the governing economic trend.\n\n\nAn important point of view that from tas\nsecurity market of to-day must be reganged 8\nthe attitude of the small investors. Transfer\nbooks on every important railroad and industrial\ncompany reveal constantly growing increase of\nstockholders\u2014notably prominent in the Pennsyl\nvania Railroad and the United States Steel\nCorporation. This is direct proof of the capacity\nof the public to gauge the existing situation\nThis feature is not new\u2014has been in evidence\never since the panic of last October\u2014and iz the\nclearest possible testimony to intelligent pubiie\ndiscrimination. Too much importance can\nscarcely be attached to this significant marist\nfeature.\nCoincident with such development is the evi\ndent favor which investors are bestowing upon\nstocks which, while at present quoted at ex\ntremely low prices, are clearly endowed with\nexceptional intrinsic value and superior man\n agement\u2014elements bound eventually to estadb\nlish materially higher market range.\nSome corroboration, apropes of this, has coms\nthis week to forecasts in this review suggesting\nthe value\u2014the sure market appreciation\u2014be\nlonging to Colorado Southern securities. Fora\ndecade no surer bargain has ever been obtain\nable.\nIt is not needed that investors should go\ngroping in the dark\u2014current earnings reports\nthis very week certifying what over and over\nagain has been declared here, progressiveness\nand earning increase for Colorado Southern\nwhile elsewhere the fashion is declines, contrac\ntion and uncertainty. Colorado Southern last\nvear showed a surplus of $1,450,060 for its main\nlines and for subordinate properties $515,000. a\ntotal of $2.2635,000\u2014out of which was paid 35380,\n000 of dividends to first preferred and second\npreferred stockholders, still leaving over SLA75~\n000 of profits accreditable to Colorado Southern\nstock.\n\n\nAnd it is not difficult to figure common stock\ndividends upon phenomenal exhibit like this\u2014\nnot little, temporary, dividends, but dividends\nthat can be large and lasting.\nIn Colorado Southern it is a continually\nmounting record\u2014a consistent yearly increase\nwhich demands to be taken into consideration.\nBack in 1893 the company was in a reccivership\nIts mileage then was larger than it is to-day\n\nHT NN TN I I I ITI NH NHN II I TRRr\u2014tati ei aii ia\nYet, with all tax allowances deductad, net eamn=\nings from 1893 to the beginning of this year\nshow year by year a regular gain till, at New\nYear's, 1308, the net increase is 1781 per cent\nIn dollars and cents the figures run like thist\nNet earnings, 1883, were $128.000. five vear\u00ae\nlater they passed $900,000; in 1202, thev reached\nup beyond $1,300,000, and at the beginning of\n1908 the twelve months preceding showed $3\u00bb\n415.000,\n\ni\n\nRecord like this is not paralieled in any cum\nrent exhibit of any progress in any railroads\nearnings anywhere.\nColorado Southern common stock is selling at\nan insignificant figure\u2014materially below one=\nhalf of what may fairly be considered its normal\nmarket value. For any investor not handicapped\nby impatience there is in this security safety\nand opportunity exceptional. Within the next\ntwelve months Colorado Southern common ought\nto be on the established dividend list.\n\nOne development probably much cioser at hand\u2019\nthan generally anticipated has to do with\nchanged conditions in the coal trade. Ar least\nthree of the great Eastern trunk lines will probe\nably divest themselves of their coal properties\u2014\nand it is not impossible that the present yeaF\nwill see the rounding out of a new comprehef=\nsive corporation which to anthracite will have\nmuch the same relation that the United States\nSteel Corporation has in iron and steel. And\nthis accomplishment, even more manifest thal\nrecently in Erie, there may be rapprochement of\ngreat financial Interests Wall Street has insisted\non scheduling as antagonistic.\nIn other coal flelds new and consequential de\nvelopments also seem approaching\u2014particulari\u00ae\nin Southern territory. The Steel Trust's acqulr\nsition of Tennessee Coal and Iron properties\nvastly increased the importance of that come\npany's basic assets: but that very coup\nindependent iron-making plants at a new\nadvantage \u2014giving hitherto unapproachsd V\nto free coal lands having in volume sultabl\u00e9\nsupplies for fron making\u2014the premier ind i\ndent holdings of this character belng incd\nin the thirty-six thousand acres owned b\u00a5 the\nAlubama Consolidated Coal and Iron Com\nwhose coal lands are supplemented by over Ld\nthousand acres of ore and limestone pro\nand by some seventy thousand acres of fam\nand timber lands, much of the latter great rat\nmineralized. Not much is ordinarily\nWall Street of investments like these, but cof\u00ae\nditions now arising promise to make them bod\nsome ways even actually dominating.\nCheap money seems one of the certainties fof\na substantial time to come\nH\nThe Financial World,","height":"35528","width":"25828"}}
